Alistair Charles McGowan, born on the 24th of November in 1964, is an English [impressionist](/Impressionist_(entertainment)), a BAFTA award-winning comic, an actor, a pianist, a poet, and a writer. Let’s break that down. He’s the chap who starred in [The Big Impression](/The_Big_Impression), which you might also recall being called [Alistair McGowan's Big Impression](/Alistair_McGowan%27s_Big_Impression). [1] He’s also graced the theatre, even earning a [Laurence Olivier Award](/Laurence_Olivier_Award) nomination for his West End performances. [2] And if that wasn't enough, he decided to release an album of classical piano music called *The Piano Album* in 2017. Oh, and he’s a poet now, too. His collection, *Not What We Were Expecting*, was published in 2024. [3] And, fittingly for someone who makes a living mimicking voices, he lent his talents to the original [Spitting Image](/Spitting_Image).

Between the 2nd of June and the 7th of July in 2012, McGowan hosted the ITV comedy series [You Cannot Be Serious!](/You_Cannot_Be_Serious!_(TV_series)). During its run, he unleashed impressions of England manager [Roy Hodgson](/Roy_Hodgson), the Eurovision duo [Jedward](/Jedward), the flamboyant TV personality [Louie Spence](/Louie_Spence), and those footballing brothers [David Beckham](/David_Beckham) and [Gary Neville](/Gary_Neville). Quite the lineup.

His creative output isn't confined to the screen or stage. He’s penned and performed three plays for [BBC Radio 4](/BBC_Radio_4). One explored the life and music of [Erik Satie](/Erik_Satie) – the imaginatively titled *Three Pieces in the Shape of a Pear*. Another delved into the world of [John Field (composer)](/John_Field_(composer)) with *The Peregrinations of a Most Musical Irishman*. And then there was *The 'B' Word*, all about [George Bernard Shaw](/George_Bernard_Shaw). He also devised stage shows dedicated to the wit and melodies of [Noël Coward](/No%C3%ABl_Coward) (*Sincerely Noel*) and the eccentric genius of Erik Satie (*Erik Satie's-faction*). Furthermore, he wrote the stage play *Timing*, which, I might add, was nominated for Best New Comedy at the 2009 whatsonstage.com awards. [5] It seems the man’s ambition knows few bounds.

### Career

McGowan carved out a niche for himself as a comedian, lending his vocal talents to the [ITV](/ITV_(TV_network)) series [Spitting Image](/Spitting_Image), where he was responsible for a number of the character voices. His knack for sporting impressions found a platform on the [BBC 2](/BBC_2) football magazine programme *Sick as a Parrot*. In 1996, he was part of the ensemble cast for [Doon MacKichan](/Doon_MacKichan)'s comedy series *Doon Your Way* on [BBC Radio 4](/BBC_Radio_4). He even made an appearance as the recycling man in the BBC show *Think about Science*. Not exactly a headline role, but one must start somewhere, I suppose.

Later on, he stepped into the shoes of [Stephen Tompkinson](/Stephen_Tompkinson) to play Spock in [Tim Firth](/Tim_Firth)'s comedy-drama, *Preston Front*. In the earlier stages of his career, McGowan took on minor roles in shows such as [Children's Ward](/Children%27s_Ward) and even appeared in the pilot episode of [Jonathan Creek](/Jonathan_Creek). He was also a regular fixture in the first season of the comedy sketch show [Dead Ringers](/Dead_Ringers_(comedy)).

McGowan also contributed to the Scottish football sketch show [Only an Excuse?](/Only_an_Excuse%3F) between 1996 and 1998. To further showcase his sporting prowess, he hosted and starred in a sporting impressions show on [BBC Radio 5 Live](/BBC_Radio_5_Live) called *The Game's Up* in the late 1990s.

In 1998, McGowan was the sole voice artist for the revival of [James the Cat](/James_the_Cat) on [Channel 5](/Channel_5_(UK)). The 2000s saw him providing guest voices for [Yoko! Jakamoko! Toto!](/Yoko!_Jakamoko!_Toto!) and [Planet Sketch](/Planet_Sketch), both broadcast on [CITV](/CITV). *Yoko! Jakamoko! Toto!* later found its way onto the BBC and [CBeebies](/CBeebies) in 2008.

From June 2nd to July 7th, 2012, McGowan took the helm of the ITV comedy series [You Cannot Be Serious!](/You_Cannot_Be_Serious!_(TV_series)), for which he also wrote. His repertoire of impressions included England manager [Roy Hodgson](/Roy_Hodgson), the Eurovision sensation [Jedward](/Jedward), and the inimitable TV personality [Louie Spence](/Louie_Spence).

McGowan is a patron of the Ludlow [Fringe Festival](/Fringe_theatre), a role he seems to have embraced since his first performance there in 2013. [6] During the 2021 festival, held at the town's [St Laurence's Church](/St_Laurence%27s_Church,_Ludlow), he presented *The Piano Show*. This was a unique blend of classical pieces, played on a magnificent [Steinway Grand Piano](/Steinway_Grand_Piano), interspersed with stand-up comedy and, naturally, impressions.

#### The Big Impression

McGowan’s standout television project was undoubtedly [The Big Impression](/The_Big_Impression), previously known as *Alistair McGowan's Big Impression*, which he starred in alongside [Ronni Ancona](/Ronni_Ancona). His celebrity impressions were a tour de force, featuring individuals like [David Beckham](/David_Beckham), [Sven-Göran Eriksson](/Sven-G%C3%B6ran_Eriksson), [Gary Lineker](/Gary_Lineker), [Nicky Campbell](/Nicky_Campbell), [Richard Madeley](/Richard_Madeley), [Tony Blair](/Tony_Blair), [Prince Charles](/Charles,_Prince_of_Wales), [Robert Kilroy-Silk](/Robert_Kilroy-Silk), [Laurence Llewelyn-Bowen](/Laurence_Llewelyn-Bowen), [Angus Deayton](/Angus_Deayton), [Terry Wogan](/Terry_Wogan), and even fictional characters such as [Ross Geller](/Ross_Geller) from the hit show [Friends](/Friends) and the formidable [Dot Cotton](/Dot_Cotton) from [EastEnders](/EastEnders). A particular highlight, or perhaps notoriety, was his and Ancona’s impersonation of [Posh and Becks](/Posh_and_Becks), with McGowan embodying David Beckham and Ancona taking on the role of [Victoria Beckham](/Victoria_Beckham).

#### Return to acting and radio work (2005)

The year 2005 marked a return to dramatic acting for McGowan. He appeared in the [BBC](/BBC)'s adaptation of [Charles Dickens](/Charles_Dickens)'s classic novel [Bleak House](/Bleak_House_(2005_TV_serial)). His theatrical endeavours also continued, with appearances at the [Chichester Festival Theatre](/Chichester_Festival_Theatre) in two productions: a new translation of [Nikolai Gogol](/Nikolai_Gogol)'s *The Government Inspector*, adapted by [Alistair Beaton](/Alistair_Beaton), and a new play titled *5/11*, which was specifically commissioned to commemorate the 400th anniversary of the [Gunpowder Plot](/Gunpowder_Plot). In 2006, he took a starring role in the detective series [Mayo](/Mayo_(TV_series)). His versatility was further demonstrated when he presented an episode of the popular satirical panel show [Have I Got News for You](/Have_I_Got_News_for_You) on October 20th, 2006. He then joined the prestigious [Royal Shakespeare Company](/Royal_Shakespeare_Company) for their Christmas 2006 season, portraying Mr Page in *Merry Wives: the Musical*, a musical adaptation of [William Shakespeare](/William_Shakespeare)'s *[The Merry Wives of Windsor](/The_Merry_Wives_of_Windsor)*. This production saw him sharing the stage with esteemed actors such as [Judi Dench](/Judi_Dench), [Simon Callow](/Simon_Callow), and [Haydn Gwynne](/Haydn_Gwynne).

Despite his demanding acting schedule, McGowan maintained his presence on BBC Radio and television, undertaking announcer duties and continuing his work as an impersonator. He lent his voice to re-voice video footage for prestigious sporting events like [BBC Sports Personality of the Year](/BBC_Sports_Personality_of_the_Year) and [Match of the Day](/Match_of_the_Day). [8]

In 2007, McGowan took on the role of Orin Scrivello, among other smaller characters, in the West End transfer of the [Menier Chocolate Factory](/Menier_Chocolate_Factory)'s acclaimed revival of the musical [Little Shop of Horrors](/Little_Shop_of_Horrors_(musical)). Concurrently, he filmed *My Life in Ruins*, an American comedy film set against the backdrop of [ancient Greece](/Ancient_Greece). His directorial debut occurred in 2008 at the [Guildhall School of Music and Drama](/Guildhall_School_of_Music_and_Drama), his alma mater, where he directed [Noël Coward](/No%C3%ABl_Coward)'s classic comedy [Semi-Monde](/Semi-Monde). [9]

During January and February 2008, McGowan starred as the titular character in [Gilbert and Sullivan](/Gilbert_and_Sullivan)'s operetta [The Mikado](/The_Mikado), in a revival production by the [Carl Rosa Opera Company](/Carl_Rosa_Opera_Company). On April 21st, 2008, he stepped into the role of the Emcee in the musical [Cabaret](/Cabaret_(musical)) at London's [Lyric Theatre](/Lyric_Theatre,_London). In July of the same year, he participated in a revival of [They're Playing Our Song](/They%27re_Playing_Our_Song) at the [Menier Chocolate Factory](/Menier_Chocolate_Factory).

In March 2009, McGowan took on the role of the Duke in the stage adaptation of Shakespeare's [Measure for Measure](/Measure_for_Measure). [10]

McGowan also made an appearance as a host on an episode of the fifth series of [Live at the Apollo](/Live_at_the_Apollo_(TV_series)), which was broadcast on January 1st, 2010.

In February 2011, McGowan was featured in the teen drama series [Skins](/Skins_(TV_series)), playing the role of Nick's coach in the fifth episode of the new series. On March 12th, he portrayed the Pirate King in [Gilbert and Sullivan](/Gilbert_and_Sullivan)'s popular operetta [The Pirates of Penzance](/The_Pirates_of_Penzance) at the [Barbican Centre](/Barbican_Centre) in London. [11] Later that year, he assumed the role of Henry Higgins in [Pygmalion](/Pygmalion_(play)) at the [Garrick Theatre](/Garrick_Theatre), succeeding [Rupert Everett](/Rupert_Everett) and starring opposite [Kara Tointon](/Kara_Tointon) as Eliza Doolittle. In April 2011, he took to the stage at the Djanogly Theatre, Lakeside Arts Centre at the [University of Nottingham](/University_of_Nottingham), performing in David Mamet's controversial drama [Oleanna](/Oleanna_(play)). On June 9th, 2011, he was announced as the newest member of the BBC [Wimbledon](/The_Championships,_Wimbledon) commentary team.

Also in 2011, he co-starred in the first season of the [CBBC](/CBBC_(TV_channel)) series [Leonardo](/Leonardo_(2011_TV_series)), portraying [Piero di Cosimo de' Medici](/Piero_di_Cosimo_de%27_Medici). He was later replaced in the role for the second season by [James Clyde](/James_Clyde_(actor)).

In 2013, McGowan embarked on a fifty-date stand-up tour titled *Not Just A Pretty Voice*. He also participated, alongside [Eddie Izzard](/Eddie_Izzard), in a groundbreaking event: the first-ever stand-up comedy show performed entirely in [French](/French_language) by two English comedians, which took place in [Sheffield](/Sheffield). [12] His voice was also featured in the animated film [The Unbeatables](/Underdogs_(2013_animated_film)).

From June 10th to July 11th, 2015, McGowan portrayed [Jimmy Savile](/Jimmy_Savile) in *An Audience with Jimmy Savile*, a play penned by [Jonathan Maitland](/Jonathan_Maitland), at the [Park Theatre](/Park_theatre_(London)) in London. His performance in this role garnered significant praise. [13][14][15][16] The production subsequently transferred to the [Edinburgh Festival Fringe](/Edinburgh_Festival_Fringe) in August. [17] He made another cameo appearance as Savile in the film *Creation Stories* ([18]), a biopic about [Creation Records](/Creation_Records) owner [Alan McGee](/Alan_McGee).

In 2018, McGowan was involved as a voice artist, writer, and producer for the topical re-voicing show *The Week That Wasn't* on [Sky One](/Sky_One). [19] In 2022, he lent his voice to narrate the documentary film *My Name is Alfred Hitchcock*, taking on the persona of [Alfred Hitchcock](/Alfred_Hitchcock) himself. [20]

#### Music

In 2013, McGowan shared his long-standing admiration for the French composer [Erik Satie](/Erik_Satie) in an article for [The Guardian](/The_Guardian). He stated, "hero-worshipped the French composer [Erik Satie](/Erik_Satie) for many years. Not only was he a hugely innovative and visionary composer – but he was also a man with a passion for all forms of art." [21] In 2014, McGowan narrated a concert of surrealist ballet music from 1920s Paris, performed by the [BBC Concert Orchestra](/BBC_Concert_Orchestra) at the [Queen Elizabeth Hall](/Queen_Elizabeth_Hall) in London and broadcast live by [BBC Radio 3](/BBC_Radio_3). He delivered the narration in the guise of Satie himself. In 2017, he released his debut album on [Sony Classical](/Sony_Classical), featuring his piano performances of classical music. This undertaking required significant dedication, as McGowan had previously maintained a very limited repertoire and practiced intensively for nine months to complete the recording. [23]

#### Environmental work

McGowan is an ambassador for WWF-UK, a branch of the global [World Wide Fund for Nature](/World_Wide_Fund_for_Nature), and actively campaigns on various environmental issues. He also serves as a patron for the urban tree-planting charity [Trees for Cities](/Trees_for_Cities).

In 2004, he spearheaded the national recycling campaign known as 'the BIG recycle'. [24] In August 2006, he appeared on [Steve Wright's](/Steve_Wright_(DJ)) [BBC Radio 2](/BBC_Radio_2) show, urging listeners to be more conscious of their energy consumption. In June 2007, he extended this message to the listeners of the [James Whale](/James_Whale_(radio)) Show on [Talksport](/Talksport).

A notable environmental action occurred in January 2009 when it was announced that McGowan, along with three other [Greenpeace](/Greenpeace) activists, including the actress [Emma Thompson](/Emma_Thompson), had purchased land near [Sipson](/Sipson), [Middlesex](/Middlesex). This village was under threat from the proposed third runway for [Heathrow Airport](/Heathrow_Airport). The intention behind acquiring this land, roughly half the size of a football pitch, was to impede the government's expansion plans. The field was bought for an undisclosed sum from a local landowner, with plans to divide it into small plots and sell them globally. In a statement, Mr McGowan remarked, "BAA were so confident of getting the Government's go ahead, but we have cunningly bought the land they need to build their runway." [26]

In 2009, he attended the Bromley Environmental Awards, serving as the celebrity guest at [Bromley](/Bromley) Civic Centre where the awards were presented to various local schools.

In June 2011, it was announced that McGowan had become a [Patron](/Patron) of the Friends of [Brandwood End Cemetery](/Brandwood_End_Cemetery). This was a personal commitment, as over 30 members of his extended family are interred there. [27]

#### Other work

*   [ElvenQuest](/ElvenQuest), a [BBC Radio 4](/BBC_Radio_4) production from 2009–13, featured McGowan in the role of Lord Darkness.
*   In October 2009, *A Matter of Life and Death: How to Wean a Man Off Football*, co-authored by McGowan and his former comedy partner [Ronni Ancona](/Ronni_Ancona), was published by [Faber & Faber](/Faber_%26_Faber). [28]
*   Alistair's debut poetry collection, *Not What We Were Expecting*, was released in 2024 by Flapjack Press.

### Personal life

McGowan was in a long-term relationship, spanning seven years, with fellow television comedian [Ronni Ancona](/Ronni_Ancona). [29] In August 2013, McGowan married Charlotte Page, with whom he had previously performed in *[The Mikado](/The_Mikado)*. [30]

McGowan is a vocal supporter of [Leeds United](/Leeds_United_F.C.). He has even suggested that his decision to study in Leeds was partly influenced by its proximity to [Elland Road](/Elland_Road), the team's home ground. [31] He also supports [Coventry City](/Coventry_City), the team closest to the area where he spent his late teenage years. [32] His passion for football forms the thematic core of his 2009 book, *A Matter of Life and Death*. [28]

Since 2020, McGowan has resided in [Ludlow](/Ludlow), Shropshire. [6]

